Density functional theory (DFT) was employed for theoretical investigation of the interactions between BR and NCQDs using 6–31 G (d,p) basis set within the GAUSSIAN-16 software [67]. The calculation of frontier molecular orbital energies for each species allowed us to determine the Highest Occupied Molecular Orbital (HOMO) and Lowest Unoccupied Molecular Orbital (LUMO) [68,69]. Utilizing the B3LYP technique, we found that the EHOMO and ELUMO for NCQDs were −3.04 eV and −1.92 eV, respectively while those for BR were −5.35 eV and −2.12 eV (as shown in Figs. 10a
                     , S4). As depicted in Fig. 10b, it is evident that photo-excited electrons in BR have sufficient energy to undergo electron transfer from NCQDs, indicating the significance of Förster Resonance Energy Transfer (FRET) as a fluorescence process. The complete energy optimization of the reactants and the resulting complex was performed using the Density Functional Theory (DFT) at the B3LYP level of theory, employing the Gaussian 16 software package. Table 2 provides information on selected bond lengths and angles. As depicted in (Fig. 11
                     ), the refined structure of the complex specifically reveals the presence of hydrogen bonds, with intermolecular hydrogen-bonded proton transfers between the highly acidic BR protons and the NCQD ring nitrogen, resulting in the bond O58H131…N13, with a bond length measuring 2.809 Å and a bond angle (N12-H131-O58) of 137.4°. These hydrogen bonds play a crucial role in facilitating the charge transfer interaction between NCQD and BR. Comparing the optimized.

Structures of NCQD and the NCQDs-BR complex (Table 2), we observe that the O58 single bond H131 is extended by 0.06 Å upon the formation of the charge transfer (CT) complex. This observation aligns By an increase of 0.002 in the Mulliken atomic charge of the formed complex O58, as shown in Table 3. Furthermore, Table 1

                      also shows a decrease in the C89O58 bond length in the complex by 0.01 Å due to the occurrence of proton transfer hydrogen (O58H131…N13).It has been observed that change in Muliken charges i.e., either increase or decrease for all the atoms has occurred after complex formation Table S.. but the H-bonded and their adjacent atoms have shown an increase in Muliken charges in the complex (Table 3
                     ). This provides strong evidence for the occurrence of charge transfer and proton transfer interactions between NCQD and BR. Similar conclusions have been drawn in prior studies [70].
